<br>
I think that we should get together and come up with a set of procedures or protocols to prevent disagreements and/or handle disputes. Some of these might be taken care of, but others are not.<br>
<br>
For instance:<br>
If RPing where hostility arises via RP, the persons should also send tells to affected parties to make sure that it isn't personal, but rather an attempt at roleplaying. I've seen instances where people get into arguments or name calling, but are really just in a state of roleplaying opposing race/classes. This may prevent some players from taking true offense at what is said and to understand that it is roleplaying, because the people around who are addressed may not be roleplaying.<br>
<br>
Respect of space: Here, we might address issues of camping as X space or area. Sometimes people choose to camp an area off to the side of a camp instead of on the &quot;campfire&quot;, which may or may not cause disputes. This is just an example of what we can establish as a *common understanding*. Some people believe that you don't *own* a spawn, where others believe in the first there, first owned rule. I think that if we get a common protocol, we can avoid disputes. Obviously, these aren't binding rules, but a set of guidelines that may prevent misunderstandings in the future. If it gets past that point, then it is between the parties involved.<br>
<br>
Some protocols may not be effective for all guilds. For instance, there may be guilds out there that condone killstealing or other activities that we may not favor as a majority. This does not mean that we don't establish a way of conflict handling. Such as...<br>
1. Direct tells to the group leaders or persons to keep it a private matter vs OOC or SHOUT fighting.<br>
2. Encouragement of mature calm discussion and spirit of compromise.<br>
3. If tempers are too hot, take a break before resuming discussion.<br>
4. Take it to the guild officers or leaders.<br>
etc.<br>
If this were posted, it might keep the number of shout and ooc fighting down, which is always a good thing. Also, it gives a sense of process to people instead of a general sense of hopeless yelling at one another.<br>
I think that the Council should get together and come up with Generally Accepted Principles of Conflict Resolution or something like that.<br>
Deo<br>
