</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#FFFFCC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub68.ezboard.com/uzendrett.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Zendrett</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#8E9173>(2/19/01 10:00:33 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub6.ezboard.com/fcouncilofguildscouncildiscussions.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=7.topic&index=5>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Etiquette</span><hr size=1> IMHO...<br>
The Council of Guilds whether they want to or not must, at some point, have to deal with governing over matters that Deo stated above about handling disputes.  It doesn't have to law, but guilds need to know that if they plan on raiding with CoG,there are guildlines that must be followed or they won't be raiding with the CoG anymore.<br>
EQ has evolved...the Alliance and the CoG will soon become governing Factors as far as Guilds are concerned.  I fret at the day the some guilds get together and form an EQ version of the Empire, and I only hope that the CoG are the rebels <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  But anyway, the CoG must be ready to step foward and be able to take a stand when problems arise.<br>
<br>
As for the Roleplaying thing...I would not recommend that when RP with others you send private tells to say your just RPing.  Instead...tack on at the end of your ooc...&quot;RPing&quot;..why?  Because all the idiots out there that feel they need to add their two cents when your RPing with another guild.  This way you dont start a shouting match by everyone in the zone.<br>
<br>
On the subject of Guild officers...that is their job.  To handle disputes between members of thier guild and with members of other guilds.  Personnaly..in the KotCT (knights of the crystal tear) I would not want the non-officers shooting their mouths off to other guilds about KSing/camp stealing or whatever.  Some one steals your kill...you ask nicely incase it was a mistake...they do it again...you inform your guild officer and let them handle it.<br>
<br>
There was something else...but I rambled to long to remember it. hehehe.. <br>
These are just my thoughts to help further the discussion.<br>
<br>
Zendrett<br>
42 Warrior<br>
Knights of the Crystal Tear <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#CBC6B1><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub68.ezboard.com/ucassia.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Cassia</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#8E9173>(2/19/01 4:23:18 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub6.ezboard.com/fcouncilofguildscouncildiscussions.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=7.topic&index=6>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://facelink.com/cassia?flezbwidth=60&flezbheight=60 WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Etiquette</span><hr size=1> I do not think that the time has come for the CoG to become a governing body.  I do not think that time will ever come.  I believe that the vision of the CoG is a place for guilds to come together and get support for and hold events.  Events of all shapes, sizes and natures.<br>
<br>
As I understand how things stand now, the person or group who runs each particular event sets the rules for that event.  They set how lottos will be done, they set how discipline will be dealt with, etc.  The Sacred Band's lotto rules might be different from Zellex's, or the Fellowship of Faydark's...etc.  I think that banning people should be handled in much the same way.  It's the right and responsibility of the raid commander and/or their managing body.  If someone is banned from one group's raids, then the others should be informed...but I don't think it's right to set a standard and hold everyone in the CoG to it.<br>
<br>
I think that would take away some of the individuality of groups that want to lead raids.  I'd much rather see each leader be responsible for discipline problems on their own raids.  We can definately communicate about such problems, and should...but aside from offenses that are banable, I don't think the CoG should be in the position of saying &quot;No, you can't come to this raid.&quot;   <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#FFFFCC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub68.ezboard.com/uplangstrump.showPublicProfile?language=EN>P Langstrump</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#8E9173>(2/19/01 4:58:08 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub6.ezboard.com/fcouncilofguildscouncildiscussions.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=7.topic&index=7>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.interlog.com/~wings/jane/a_lindgren/lindgren_pics/pippi.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Etiquette</span><hr size=1> There is already a lot of pressure put on the few people who are willing to spend time and efforts keeping this alive.  I personally do it because I don't see it being done anywhere. I see guilds and alliance creating all these rules and wanting to be governing powers, but that's what consumes a most of their time, too.  If people want to form their own power version of an empire, you know what will happen? I will quit this game, with no regret.<br>
<br>
All I would expect to see here is what constitutes a right to kick someone off of a CoG raid and blacklist him/her.  Basically:<br>
- ninjalooting<br>
- kill stealing<br>
- verbal abuse and disrespect to any individuals in a public way, such as racist, sexist or derogatory remarks shouts or OOCs directed at a person<br>
- blatant use of means that results in harming the rest of the group at an event, that is, purposefully causing deaths or loss of equipment<br>
